In this paper we aim to describe the propagation
of a "failure event" through a metabolic network
(i.e. no formation of a set of metabolites) and,
by means of a Markov chain, to be able to compute the long-run failure probability of each
metabolite following a transient random failure event occurring
somewhere in the network. Moreover, we
will introduce and motivate the definition of a "tolerance index" for each metabolite.
The <em>in silico</em>
analysis reveals that in most of the 142 organisms'
metabolic network we considered, such tolerance index
is approximately uniformly distributed among
nodes with the same in-degree, while the failure distribution
and the connection degree is not. A list
of metabolites ranked by failure probability and tolerance
index for all the 142 organism is also provided in the <a href="http://www.dis.uniroma1.it/~farina/robustness/">
